    Russian fascism's main home was outside Europe, in Manchuria. The Russian Fascist Party, modelled on Mussolini's movement, was founded in the city of Harbin in 1931. Here, on the remote reaches of the Sungary river, thousands of Russians who had fled from the revolution constructed a little Russia. In a city teeming with different nationalities, the Russians printed and read numerous papers in Russian, attended the Russian cathedral, sat in cafes along the smart Bolshoi Prospekt, and talked endlessly of the war of revenge against Bolshevism. The White community was fractions and diverse, and Soviet agents encouraged their squabbles.


something like this going on in Chowchilla?


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla
	A Decade-old Crime Holds A Small Town Hostage
	July 20, 1986
	By Linda Witt

	CHOWCHILLA, CALIF. — Edward Ray, 65, has a 26-foot Winnebago sitting out back of his house by the old dairy barn and a new $125 gold watch the Dairyland School gave him in June when he officially retired after 33 years as a school bus driver. When summer school is over this week (he still is driving the bus this summer), he and his wife, Odessa, may try out their new vehicle on a trip to Washington State.

	Then, maybe, finally, Edward--even the kids on his school bus call him Edward--will be able to let go of the memories that have haunted him and this little farm and ranch community of 5,000 for a decade.

	The memories are so mixed--despite a bookcase full of trophies, plaques, letters of appreciation (including one from President Ford) and good words spoken of Ray for the Congressional Record. No one brought them up at the cake and coffee party that marked his retirement. And the 10th anniversary of the harrowing event that made Ray and this quiet village famous was allowed to pass without fanfare last Tuesday.


https://www.newspapers.com/image/383018551/?terms=%22Edward%2BRay%2BDay%22
	18 Jul 1976

	...Ray is a humble man, a resident of Chowchilla since 1921 who was born in the nearby town of Le Grand.

	...After countless interviews and questions from hundreds of newspersons and after only 1 1/2 hours of sleep, Ray consented to still another interview.

	...He seemed a little embarrassed when told the townspeople are planning a "Frank Edward Ray Day" to honor th man they credit with saving their children.

	How does it feel to be a hero? "I don't know," he answered, turning the conversation to the "good people" in law enforcement who helped the rescue efforts.


https://www.newspapers.com/image/15448155/?terms=Chowchilla
	17 Jul 1976

	'He's the best'

	Bus driver proves hero

	CHOWCHILLA, Calif. (UPI) -- "Mr. Ray, he's the best," chanted a group of children when asked who their favorite bus driver was.

	Frank Ray Jr., 55, is also a real homespun hero today after digging himself and 26 children from a cavern prison near Livermore, Calif.

	...Ray, his bright blue eyes flashing, said he did most of the digging that freed the children and himself from a cavern at the bottom of a rock quarry where they had been left 16 hours earlier by gunmen.

	"I'd crawl up there and dig for awhile. I had plenty of water. I'd go back and get some water, splash it over my face and I'd go back up and dig some more."


http://www.mercedsunstar.com/news/local/community/chowchilla/article9308183.html?fb_comment_id=697011047075617_697094400400615
	Chowchilla hero to be honored

	A park in Chowchilla will be renamed later this month in honor of Ed Ray, the unassuming bus driver who made national news when he helped free 26 kidnapped students.

	The city of Chowchilla and Ray’s family are planning a ceremony near where Sonoma Avenue meets the 625 North 15th Street park at 4 p.m. Feb. 26, which would have been Ray’s 94th birthday. He died in 2012, grabbing headlines as news outlets around the country remembered him as a hero.

	...Glen Ray, 69, said he appreciates the city’s effort to honor his father, though he noted his father never considered himself a hero.

	“My father was a very simple man. He never thought that this was a heroic act,” he said. “This was his job. These kids were entrusted in his care, and it’s his job to get them home safely.”


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla
	``People feel they`ve closed the door on a bad experience,`` the editor of the local Chowchilla News told a visiting reporter. ``And they want to keep it closed.``


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla/4
	...Jodi Heffington, now 20, is a beautician in Chowchilla and won`t talk about the kidnaping. One of the four Cerrejo girls on the bus, Irene Reimer, now 21, married, and working at the local hospital, says, ``It`s just a bad dream; we don`t want to talk about it.``

	Pretty Cindy Van Hoff, 17, an honor student who won nine varsity letters, got her diploma in June. She shrugs off her memories, ``There`s nothing to be learned from it. It was just a freak thing.`` Many students refuse to talk about the incident at all, to the point of angrily lecturing reporters who call. ``Look, we didn`t ask to be famous,`` one said. ``Let us alone.``


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla
	``Chowchilla. . . . Whenever I tell a stranger that`s where I`m from, a quizzical look comes across their face,`` says former Mayor Jim Dumas. ``And then they remember. `Oh, yes,` `` he says slowly, unconsciously mimicking the slow, dawning of recognition on such a stranger`s face. `` `The kidnaping.`

	...Principal Lee Roy Tatom recalls how puzzled he was when he got the first call from a worried parent: ``Hey, the little guy isn`t home yet.`` Tatom thought maybe the old bus had broken down along the road--Ray often had to fix the bus himself from parts he`d buy at Emmett McDonald`s auto supply.

	``I went out and traced Edward`s bus route. . . . When I`d gone over the whole thing east and west, I went back and went north and south. . . . I called the county police and asked if they`d seen a yellow school bus floating around, but . . . God, what could have happened? The whole thing was impossible to comprehend.``

	The one thing he didn`t worry about was Edward Ray. The man had been born in Chowchilla. Everybody knew his wife and his two boys and his grandchildren. Some of the kids on the bus were the grandkids of his own school classmates. Others were the children of kids he`d driven years before. Everybody in town knew the bashful, balding man with the ready smile.

	...Despite an air tube, suffocation was a real possibility. Ray admits that he cried as well as prayed, and he tried to keep the children calm. When they moved around, the timbers and wires would creak and groan. Several times, Ray thought the severely stressed roof would cave in on them.

	What happened next is still subject to debate. In the weeks afterward, Mike Marshall, the oldest boy on the bus, later claimed that it was he who started digging the kids out. Some of the other children, but by no means all, recalled it that way, too. Marshall, then 14, was was the son of a rodeo cowboy. His dad was up at the Calgary Stampede, competing. Mike had to stay home for the summer to make up credits in summer school. Usually he spent his afternoons practicing with his lasso and dreaming of cowboying. He wasn`t even supposed to be on the bus the day of the kidnaping, but his mom had gotten mad at him that morning and made him stay at school and ride home with the littler kids as punishment.

	``He was a skinny little guy,`` Ray recalls now, with a smile. ``He was one of those boys who smoked and dipped Copenhagen snuff. The janitor`d catch `em. You could smell it when he got on the bus.``


https://www.newspapers.com/image/30719036/
	14 Nov 1976

	In a town divided, Chowchilla now asks: Who was the hero?

	By MICHAEL COAKLEY

	...It could be any American farm town approaching Thanksgiving, its blessings apparent to the most casual observer.

	But Chowchilla is not just any town, and the crime the four months ago brought it lasting notoriety has left some deep scars, so deep that some of its people doubt they will ever heal.

	The 26 children who were kidnaped off their school bus and shoved into a quarry pit for nearly 17 hours are back in their classrooms now. The bus driver, Ed Ray, is off the celebrity circuit and back on his old route.

	But nothing is really normal again. Several of the children suffer psycological after-effects: many of the parents are resentful that so much attention has been centered on Ray; Ray, in turn, is embittered toward the parents; and throughout the community there is fear, also a touch of greed.

	"I don't think we'll ever get over this thing completely; there are just too many problems," said Mayor Jim Dumas. "The best we can do is put it out of our minds as much as possible and get on with living."

	...And in Chowchilla, the victims of the abduction and their families are finding that memories of the ordeal simply won't fade, partyl because of the massive publicity that continues to envelop of the the century's most bizarre crimes.

	Ray has become a folk hero, honored by countless public officials and service clubs as the man responsible for digging the children out of the pit and saving their lives. Two weeks ago he made a guest appearance on the TV game show "Hollywood Squares."

	All this fawning over Ray has grated on some parents. While expressing gratitude toward the stocky, 55-year-old driver for keeping the children calm during their joint captivity, many townspeople are convinced the biggest hero was actually Mike Marshall, a lanky 14-year-old who tugged for five hours to free the group while Ray, according to some of the children, at one point tried to discourage him from continuing.

	"I don't understand why the media isn't paying more attention to Mike Marshall and the other kids who played such a big role," said one of the parents privately. "I guess it's just easier to make a hero out of a father figure, but I do think the children feel neglected and cheated, and this aggravates the whole problem."

	...Marshall, the oldest of the children held captive, said he first got the idea of attempting an escape soon after the group had stopped hearing sounds from above, indicating the kidnapers had left the quarry site.

	"I started digging, and Ed Ray took me over in the corner and told me it was no use, that we weren't going to get out of there and we'd just have to kick the bucket," Marshall recalled. "I was stunned when he said that, but after a little while I started digging again."

	Eventually, he added, Ray did assist in pushing away the heavy metal plate that the kidnapers had used to cover the hole. Marshall believes he could not have moved the plate without the driver.


https://www.newspapers.com/image/389149632
	16 Jan 1983

	...[Mike] said he no longer has the bad dreams but he said that when he thinks back to July, 1976, "it's scary. I mena, I remember how scared I was. When Ed Ray told me that we were going to die if we stayed down there, kick the bucket, that right there is what made me want to dig out. I figured if I was going to die down there, then I might as well die trying to dig out. Because he (Ray) was an adult, I thought he knew what he was talking about.

	...Mike said he sometimes looks back on the time in the buried truck-trailer and he marvels at what he and Robert Gonzales accomplished. "I don't think I could do it right now--if I didn't think I was going to die. It's like the story you hear of the kid lifting the car off his dad. It got his adrenalin flowing. It was kind of like that."


https://www.newspapers.com/image/30719036/
	Two other children who were in the quarry confirmed Marshall's story. "It was Mike's idea to start digging, I remember that for sure." said 11-year-old Jeff Brown. His 9-year-old sister, Jennifer, complained that Ray has been honored too much and that he had resigned himself to not escaping. "He said why bother to try and get out of there: we were going to die there and we should save our strength," she recollected.

	Marshall's mother does not join those who criticize Ray. "I really was angry about it for a long time, because I do think Mike was the real hero; but if this fame is what Ed needs, then I think we should let him have it," she said. "Besides, the nation needed a hero, and I guess a 14-year-old boy just wouldn't do."

	Ray himself is hurt by the comments of the parents. Standing by his bus in front of the Dairyland School waiting for the children to come out -- as he did on that humid day in July -- the man could not hide his anger.

	"I'm going over there and straighten out that kid Marshall one of these days, but people tell me I oughtn't do it when I'm mad," he said.

	"I'm the one that god those kids out of that hole, and I don't know why everybody's going around lying about it. Some of these damn parents won't even let me talk to their kids now. They think I'm getting too much credit, and that it was the kids that did it all."

	Acknowledging that there were things he would have done differently in hindsight, he added: "I thought I did pretty good just getting everybody out of there."

	Mayor Dumas admits there has been some resentment of Ray in Chowchilla. "And frankly, I think it's totally unjustified," he added. "I'm convinced those kids never would have been freed if it hadn't been for Ed Ray."


https://www.newspapers.com/image/42432147/?terms=mike%2BMarshall%2BChowchilla
	02 Jul 1977

	By Joseph N. Bell

	...The Marshalls are at the center of a controversy that has divided Chowchilla deeply. Mike hopes to collaborate with a local reporter on a book that will state that it was Mike and not Ed Ray, the bus driver, who was responsible for digging the children out of their underground prison.

	Carol enlarges, uneasy but determined. "It's caused some dissension here. I know that. But I think a lot of people are now regretting some things that happened after the kidnapping. The public made a big thing of it all over the world. Then there was this big letdown afterward when all the recognition and credit went to one person. This picture of one adult leading the kids out simply wasn't so, at least from the point of view of many of the kids. Each one of the kids thinks he or she played a big part in getting out -- even if they didn't do anything physically."

	Ed Ray, a stocky, barrel-chested man with the calloused hands of a manual worker, still drives his Chowchilla school bus daily. "There's some awful far-out stories being told," he said to me. "Like in some of those stories, the boys done all the work, and I didn't do nothing but lay down there in that hole and pray. I don't think that's fair to me."

	Ray said he heard from several motion picture producers, and had signed a 90-day option with one. He now doubts anything will ever come of the whole matter, however. "Now, I'm just back to the same old routine, driving my bus and going my other work. For a long while I was thinking about it all the time. Now that's pretty well stopped -- till somebody brings it up like right now, and then it starts all over again."

	An Ed Ray Retirement Fund and a Scholarship Fund for the children were established...


