	Mike pointed out that it was Gonzales who first broke through into open air after digging out of the van--and he (Mike), who first climbed to freedom.

	"I was scared to go out there," he said. "I didn't know if the kidnapers were still there..."

	Mike had nothing but praise for Ray.

	But he said a "lot of the news reports of this things--how we got out and all--are wrong. We were the ones, Robert and me, who wanted to start digging. Not Mr. Ray. Ed didn't want us to try to get out because he thought the kidnapers were still out there."

	Mike said he decided several times to try and dig his way out, despite Ray's objections. "We started digging again," he said, "because the other kinds wanted us to."

	Gonzales supported young Marshall's story. "It was the kids--Mike and me--who kept trying," he said. "It's nothing against Mr. Ray. He helped us, kept us cool by dousing us with water. But everyone seems to have the idea that he did the whole thing alone."

	Several parents agreed the children were not getting enough credit.

	"The kids don't understand why they were pushed into the background on this thing," said John D. Brown III, who had two children on the bus.

	But it was his daughter, Jennifer Brown, who made a special presentation to Ray from the children as a group at the climax of the ceremonies at the fairgrounds.

	There was one indication during the ceremony that Mike Marshall's special efforts had not been entirely overlooked.

	The names of the kidnaped children were read and the audience had been asked to hold their applause until the end. But when Marshall's name was read, there was applause from many of the parents.

	It wasn't much.

	But it was something, and later Sheriff Ed Bates said he had personally recommended that Younger present the special awards to Marshall, Gonzales and Ray.

	All in all, it was a gala day for everyone--and especially for Ray.

	"I don't really feel like a hero," he said. "But for the past month, everybody has been telling me that I am. . ."

	...But a local clergyman helped put the whole thing in perspective:

	"It could easily have been a different story," he said. "Instead of having this celebration, today could have been a day of mourning. We have that to be thankfull for.

	"Beside this fact, nothing else is really to important . . ."


https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/jul/15/las-vegan-mike-marshall-remembers-his-role-helping/
	Las Vegan Mike Marshall remembers his role helping children escape the terrifying Chowchilla kidnapping

	Lisa Ferguson

	Thursday, July 15, 1999

	Did he or didn't he?

	It's the question that has trailed Las Vegan Mike Marshall for more than two decades.

	Was he -- on July 15, 1976, at age 14 -- responsible for conceiving and implementing a plan that saved the lives of 25 youngsters who, along with himself and a school bus driver, were buried alive for more than a dozen hours in a moving-van trailer by a trio of gun-toting kidnappers in Chowchilla, Calif.?

	Or should credit have gone to the school bus driver, Ed Ray, who reportedly helped Marshall and some of the other boys execute the escape?

	The debate continues today, 23 years after the much-publicized crime landed the small, central-California farming community in the media spotlight.

	In the first few years following the kidnapping Marshall -- a longtime rodeo rider who these days divides his time between his home in East Las Vegas and a construction job in Phoenix -- couldn't have cared less whether his heroics were lauded.

	But as time passes, and peoples' queries about the events of the kidnapping continue, 37-year-old Marshall wonders if the truth will ever be known.

	"I thought during the years that it really didn't bother me," he says by phone from Phoenix.

	Having competed on the professional rodeo circuit from 1980-92 (and being the son of rodeo rider Bob Marshall), he says people in that industry were familiar with his story as a victim of the Chowchilla school bus kidnapping.

	But occasionally news programs and magazines will profile Ray, who subsequently purchased the Dairyland School bus involved in the kidnapping.

	"They'd see (Ray) on some tabloid show and they'd say, 'They didn't even mention (Marshall's) name,' " he says.

	To hear Marshall tell his version of the events -- he was the subject of a People magazine profile and a feature on NBC's "Dateline" this spring -- it would seem the then-teenager took it upon himself to bring the schoolchildren, Ray and himself back alive.

	...For all the children and Ray knew, they had been left to die.

	Marshall says the 27 victims were forced to rely on a single air vent. Some rations -- water and a bit of food -- and a few mattresses and box springs and a pair of crude toilets were provided. Meanwhile the trailer's roof began to collapse from the weight that had been placed upon it.

	As Marshall tells it, "The bus driver totally freaked out. He told me it looked like we were gonna have to stay down there and kick the bucket. ... I noticed he wasn't handling the situation very good, but I thought, 'Well, if this guy thinks we're gonna kick the bucket, what the heck am I doing down here?' "

	At that point, Marshall says, he kicked apart one of the box springs and used pieces of its wooden frame to wedge up the iron plate covering the hole far enough to get his fingers around it and move it out of the way. Then he claims to have moved the truck batteries and crawled inside the plywood box (actually five pieces of wood that were not nailed together).

	Using a piece of wood, he dug at the plywood until he created a hole; dirt began falling down the sides and inside the trailer. He figures the process took six or seven hours.

	"I didn't know where I was going or what I was doing," he recalls. "... And the whole time, the bus driver is yelling, 'Pretty please, don't hurt him, pretty please, don't hurt him. He don't know what he's doing.' He thought (the kidnappers) were still up there."

	Marshall thought they might have been, too. "I didn't really know what I was doing but I figured it was better than doing nothing. God, you know, Jesus or whatever gave me the power," he says.

	All the while, he says, the other children cheered him on, saying, "Go Mike. You can do it, Mike."

	Larry Park, 6 at the time, was one of them. He was on the bus that day with his 8-year-old sister, Andrea.

	"Mike was the one (who) initially started digging. Mike was the one (who) took the initiative," Park, now 29 and living near California's Yosemite National Park, says.

	Marshall says he was finally able to move the the top panel of the box enough to get his fingers underneath it and lift it up, exposing the group once again to the outside world.

	"I didn't even hesitate, I just stuck my head up through (the hole) and (saw that) we were in the mountains," he says. "There were trees and stuff. It was great not seeing anybody there, too."

	Soon after, he says, Ray began handing him the children from the trailer. After they were all outside, Ray came up through the hole and pulled Marshall out last.

	As the rest of the group headed toward the rock quarry, Marshall says he ran into the nearby woods. "I thought, 'Everybody's out, but if these guys are hanging around here, and if they're gonna get them, at least I'll be free to get some help or whatever.' "

	Marshall says he stayed in the woods for about 30 minutes, until he saw police helicopters and SWAT officers approaching, and figured it was safe to join the others.

	So, what exactly was Ray's role in the mechanics of the escape?

	According to Park, "Ed Ray was pretty much a lost cause" inside the trailer. "He basically had his head in his hands and was pretty much mumbling to himself, saying we were gonna die. He didn't give us much of a chance, really."

	Ray denied such claims in a People magazine article earlier this year. Sarcastically, he said, "Oh yeah, (Marshall) done it all, I cried boo-hoo and didn't do nothing." (Attempts to reach Ray for comment for this article were unsuccessful.)

	Park admits, "Once Mike started making some headway Ed Ray joined in. I guess in his own right, Ed Ray is kind of a hero, because without him we probably never could have gotten the (iron plate) up high enough for Mike to scoot the batteries off of it. He was there towards the end of it with Mike."

	Still, "If it wasn't for Mike, we'd probably still be down there," he says. "Mike's my hero."

	San Francisco psychologist Dr. Lenore Terr has interviewed most of the Chowchilla kidnapping victims as part of an on-going study, the results of which are scheduled to be released in two years, on the 25th anniversary of the crime. She also penned a book, "Too Scared to Cry" (Basic Books, 1992), about the subject.

	Terr says that during her interviews the children were "virtually unanimous in mentioning two boys, Mike Marshall being the leader of those boys, who dug them out and who got the idea of digging them out." (She did not divulge the name of the second boy.)

	...When the children and Ray arrived safely back in Chowchilla -- some 30 hours after they had been abducted -- they found themselves in the midst of a media frenzy. Reporters from throughout the country had converged on the town and tied up phone lines so that even the kidnappers had been unable to place a call to demand their ransom.

	The media, Marshall says, "jumped on me and I started telling them what happened." But, he says, the Dairyland School's principal, Lee Roy Tatom, and Marshall's father quickly called them off.

	Marshall instead spent the next few days retelling his tale to FBI officials. "It was kind of weird because they didn't really want to talk to anyone else, just me."

	But as soon as his interrogation was through Marshall says he headed out of town with his father -- passing on the town picnic and trip to Disneyland that were awarded to the other kidnapping victims.

	A press conference was held the day after the kidnapping victims returned, where Ray explained the events to reporters. Tatom oversaw the gathering.

	"That's the time that Ed explained what happened, but I don't remember him telling (reporters) that he was the one responsible" for orchestrating the escape, Tatom says. "I don't recall Ed saying, 'I did this' or 'I did that.' "

	In fact, Tatom says "there's no doubt in my mind that Ed Ray" was responsible for the executing the escape.

	"They type of person he is, the man that he is ... it took a lot of power and a lot of muscles to do such" heavy lifting, Tatom says. While he doesn't doubt the children helped in the escape, he says, "I think because of Ed Ray that things came out a lot better than if an adult had not been there."

	Marshall says it seemed like the media "ran with this Ed Ray thing without even finding out what happened. It was like there was nothing I could really do."

	...He says he "very seldom" thinks about the kidnapping or his heroic efforts. His fiance, Sherry Bozek, recently reminded him: " 'You saved these kids' lives. They wouldn't be alive today' " if it wasn't for him.

	"I don't think of myself as a hero at all," he says. "I think that God had me in (the trailer) for a reason, and anybody else probably would have done the same thing."

	Nor does Marshall resent the attention Ray has received over the years for his reported role in the escape.

	"It just kind of blows me away," he says. The kidnapping has been "like his whole life, and it was the last thing in my life that I wanted to remember. So, I figure one day he's gonna have to answer for it and I really try not to judge."

	So he did what he could: He tried to forget. "I don't know, I didn't think anybody really cared," he says.


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla
	Whoever started digging out--Ray says it was him--what certainly did happen was that Ray, with the help of Marshall and other boys, stacked the mattresses to the ceiling and used wooden slats they knocked out of bedsprings to pry a narrow opening. Ray managed to reach up and inch off the two massive tractor batteries holding down the heavy steel plate. ``I was about give out,`` Ray says with a shake of his head. ``I worked a ranch all my life, and that week I`d been bucking baled hay--(throwing on a wagon) 140-, 160-pound bales, but that plate was heavy. I tried laying on my back and pushing at it with my legs.`` He and Mike poured water on their heads to keep from fainting with heat and exhaustion.

	In interviews after the kidnaping, Mike Marshall conceded that he could never have gotten the huge plate off by himself, but his mother maintained,

	``I do think Mike was the real hero; but if this fame is what Ed needs, then I think we should let him have it. Besides, the nation needed a hero and I guess a 14-year-old boy just wouldn`t do.``

	Ray, Marshall and two other boys sweated and strained for four or five hours in the stifling heat near the ceiling of their tomb. Finally, about 8 p.m., more than 16 hours after they`d been buried, 28 hours after they`d been abducted, they broke through, and Ray led his woozy pack of swimsuit-clad kids to the nearest structure--a maintenance shed at a nearby quarry. A stunned worker called the sheriff and gave Ray, dressed only in his cowboy boots and undershorts, a pair of coveralls.

	...In those first weeks after the kidnaping, some wonderful things happened. The Lions Club of Buena Vista, Calif., sent Ray, all the kids and their parents to Disneyland. Mayor Dumas recalls that trip. ``Wherever Edward Ray was there`d be children hanging on him. There was a kinship there that was out of the ordinary. He`s a wonderful person.`` Chowchilla threw a parade and an ``Edward Ray and the Children Appreciation Day.`` Money came in from all over the country for a retirement fund for Ray and a scholarship fund for the kids.

	Then it was all over--to the world, but it wasn`t all over at all for Chowchilla. ``My whole life is consumed by it,`` Joan Brown whose 8-year-old Jennifer and 11-year-old Jeff were on the bus, said a few months after the kidnaping. ``I quit my job. I relive it and relive it. The children suffer nightmares.`` Interviewed again last week, she said that hardly a day goes by that she doesn`t think about the terror.

	...Joan Brown said back then, ``You walk into a store to buy a magazine with a `Chowchilla` story in it and the storekeeper says, `Boy I wish they`d drop it.` Maybe people are saying this to us. We`ve been called publicity hounds.`` Mayor Dumas was quoted then saying, ``Some folks feel like the parents won`t let it die. There`s been a change in this town. I don`t understand it.`` A lot of people, Ed Ray and former Mayor Dumas included, now blame much of the aftermath on the press. ``As soon as you people stopped coming, why that took care of it,`` Dumas said a week before this week`s anniversary. He said it nicely. He likes reporters.

	What Dumas is referring to is a nasty spat of rumors that suggested Ray hadn`t done all he might have to save the kids, or done it soon enough, or done it without prodding from two of the older boys on the bus, though they all came out alive. Most of the rumors, it seemed to locals, started with reporters`questions. ``They`d get one kid or parent over here and ask one thing, then get somebody else over there and say `Well, this person says this and such,``` Ray says, his soft voice suddenly hard-edged. At its peak, the hoard of press numbered 320 there at one time; but over the next several weeks, 500 reporters would pass through town -- one for every 10 residents.


https://www.newspapers.com/image/389149632
	January 16 1983

	...While Robert appears intact emotionally today, he remembers the kidnaping and escape down to the last detail and can recite even the words spoken in the dungeon as if they were engraved in his memory.

	He remembers Ed Ray repeating again and again, "I want to see my grandchildren once more. I want to see my grandchildren once more."


https://www.newspapers.com/image/30719036/
	..."It was Mike's idea to start digging, I remember that for sure." said 11-year-old Jeff Brown. His 9-year-old sister, Jennifer, complained that Ray has been honored too much and that he had resigned himself to not escaping. "He said why bother to try and get out of there: we were going to die there and we should save our strength," she recollected.


http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1986-07-20/features/8602220197_1_school-bus-bus-driver-chowchilla
	``We were the biggest story of 1976,`` Dumas says. ``Most of the reporters were very polite. Nice folks individually. But most didn`t understand little towns. Within a two week period, we were no longer front page news every place in the world; and when the press started leaving us alone the bad feelings subsided.``

	Except Ed Ray`s feelings. ``Oh, I got over it,`` he says, but his wife, who has been wrapping fried chicken for the refrigerator of their neat farm home as she listens, disagrees. ``I don`t know you`re over it. It still bothers you,`` she interjects.

	Then she explains to a visitor, ``I know a lot of nights he still doesn`t sleep. I know when things are bothering him. He`ll go along for awhile, then it`ll come back. It has been very hard on him.``

	``What hurt more than the kidnaping,`` Ray says now, ``was the talk the parents might sue me. When I`d go into town, somebody`d tap me on the shoulder and say `I hear you are getting sued.` Everything was in my name--the house, the farm; and I was helping my two boys get started farming. We`d have lost everything.``

	...There were two quickie books written and talk of others. A self-described movie producer showed up and tried to sign everyone involved to a movie deal but not everyone would sign. Last year, HBO announced it would be making a movie; Edward Ray says he doesn`t think it`s ever going to happen.

	If it did, Lee Roy Tatom thinks Ray would be the perfect hero. ``Oh, I know Edward didn`t do it all himself. But he was the leader. He was calm and mature. I`d like to believe all my bus drivers or anybody could have done what he did, but in hindsight I`m glad it was Edward Ray on that bus. If you wrote the story as a book, you`d want Edward and a happy ending.``




kidnapping survivor Larry Park book on event:


https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Chowchilla_Kidnapping_Why_Me.html?id=SFJPvgAACAAJ
	The Chowchilla Kidnapping: Why Me?: Revised Edition

	...Jul 26, 2016

	...Mike Marshal is my hero. He was fourteen when we were kidnapped, a big kid and quite strong. His dad was a rodeo rider, and I'm sure Mike himself worked outdoors quite a bit moving hay and riding horses and stuff. For a fourteen-year-old kid to have the gumption to stand up and say no to Death takes a lot of courage. He knew what he was going to do might get him killed, but he took the ultimate step for twenty-seven people to survive . . . to live. I don't know what would have happened that day if Mike hadn't been there, but I do know that, because he *was* there, I am here on Earth to write this book.

	"Let me see the light, Mr. Ray." Mike's voice seemed to come from far away. Ed Ray turned the light on and handed it to Mike. Shining the light upward, he took a long look at the steel plate covering the hole.

	"I've tried the plate, Mike. It's too heavy to move."

	...They were sitting together on top of the matresses with the flashlight shining on the cover talking about the objects on top of the plate and what they were going to do to move them. "I can't move whatever they are, Ed Ray. I can't keep my balance, and they're just too heavy."

	Ed Ray must have begun losing heart, because he started talking as if their efforts were futile. I overheard him tell Mike it might be better to wait and see if the men came back.

	"And what if they don't come back? What if they've left us here to die?" Mike didn't want to give up.

	But Ed Ray was done. He told Mike sometimes it's better to just accept their defeat. Fatigue, feat, frustration, all had to be taking their toll on him. I know *I* didn't feel very hopeful about our situation. I didn't think I would ever see Mom or Dad again. How did he feel as he sat there thinking about his wife? I don't know what he thought during our hours of captivity, but I *do* know the despair hopelessness brings, and I don't blame him for anything he said during those worst of moments.

	"We have to keep on trying Mr. Ray. We can't just let ourselves die in here, and I can't do this alone. Please help me." Mike was desperate. He knew we had to get out of the hole and that he was going to need Ed Ray's help to make it happen.

	Ed Ray just didn't have it in him to continue going though, and just sat in the corner waiting for whatever was going to happen.

	...they pushed and lifted the plate again, higher this time. Mike pushed on the batteries some more and was able to make them move a little, but it took so long to get them to budge that, once again the two boys, in their fatigue, let the lid fall back into place.

	Ed Ray looked at the boys as they sat to rest. He said they should stop before one of them got hurt or the men came back and they got themselves in trouble. It was just too risky to keep going.

	"We can't stop. We have to get out of here. If you'd help us, we could get the plate off." Ed Ray shook his head, but Mike pressed his point. "Ed Ray, I know you're tired, I am too. But we can't just give up. Not yet." They needed Ed Ray's added strength to get the plate higher. Escape was our only chance for survival and Mike knew it. He looked at Ed Ray hopefully.

	"Okay," Ed Ray spoke in a heavy sigh. "Let's give it one more try. We'll see what we can do."


Ray's account:

https://www.newspapers.com/image/98252946/
	Bus Driver Tells of Kidnap, Terror, Escape

	BY ALTON SLAGLE

	New York News
	
	..."They had this building (the truck trailer) all lined with big ol' mesh wire. They stood on the outside and we could hear them cutting the wires and the ceiling started to cave in. We thought we were gonna' have it right then. We kept beggin' them to let us out.

	"In the afternoon we never did hear 'em cutting the wires no more, so me and a couple of the boys decided we'd better start diggin. When we started to move this steel plate, we couldn't hardly move it because it had two great big ol' batteries on top of it. One of the batteries I couldn't even lift myself. I had to get the kids to help me. We had to pile up mattresses and stuff to get as close enough to the whole to get out.

	"They had another big box filled about 30 inches high. They had dirt piled on each side and the top and we couldn't start to move it. It's just lucky we had a short block of wood in a thing there they had for a brace, and we used it to pry.

	"We'd throw water over our heads to try to cool off and go up and dig some more. I'd say it was about 7 o'clock we got dug out. I handed the kids up to the other boys and we got out. Just lucky enough there was a gravel pit there within 200 feet of us and there was a man over there so we told him what happened. He went and called the sheriff, and the sheriffs and the fire trucks and everything else came and we had a big crowd and we all got home safe."

	...The abductors had cut small hoes in the metal sides of the 8- by 16-foot prison so that the children could have a toilet of sorts. But the air inside was stifling, and, Ray said, it became increasingly difficult to breathe.

	He said the kidnappers said nothing to him except to ask his name and, "I never did as much as hear 'em speak to one another."

	But the frightened children made up for it, "and I just talked to 'em and begged 'em not to holler and scream that we're gonna' try to get out of here."

	...When they started cutting the wire mesh, and the dirt started caving in, Ray became fearful that the men meant to kill their prisoners. "That's the only thing I thought about," he said.


kidnap survivor Lynda Carrejo-Labendeira interview:

https://www.npr.org/2012/05/22/153308664/school-bus-driver-who-saved-students-was-a-hero
	Many of the children trapped in the bus stayed in touch with Ed Ray, even visited him in his final days at the nursing home.

	LYNDA CARREJO-LABENDEIRA: He had the lives of 26 children that he loved and cared about in his hands. He was the hero.

	...CORNISH: Masked gunmen drove Ed Ray and the 26 kids to a rock quarry about 100 miles away. They forced the group into a storage trailer, which was then buried underground. The kidnappers planned to ask for a $5 million ransom. Lynda Carrejo-Labendeira remembers how Ray and some of the older kids found an opening in the trailer and began to dig their way out.

	CARREJO-LABENDEIRA: Edward was down in there and he was right up there digging 'til he cut his hands and his forehead and there were no tools to dig with, so he - they had to makeshift whatever they could find around them. And I remember Edward being cut and pouring water on his hands and helping clean them. That was, you know, the best I knew how to do.

	CORNISH: After 16 nerve-wracking hours underground, the children and Ray managed to dig their way out unharmed. The three kidnappers were caught weeks later and sentenced to life in prison. They remain behind bars today. Lynda Carrejo-Labendeira says all these years later it was important to stay in touch with her old bus driver, Ed Ray.

	CARREJO-LABENDEIRA: It's when you go through an ordeal together, you don't even have to talk about the ordeal ever again and we really didn't. We knew what happened and it was just an unsaid thing that you knew happened and that you knew that was your hero. But also, growing up, becoming a responsible adult is when I really realized the true hero that he was.

	CORNISH: In what way?

	CARREJO-LABENDEIRA: Setting the tone of the whole ordeal, just being the role model for all of us, keeping us calm and not overreacting or acting against what the kidnappers were doing. He was calm. He was a positive presence. He was comforting. He was caring. He was kind.

	...CORNISH: Did it feel like you guys had a sort of responsibility to him, I mean, collectively in the community?

	CARREJO-LABENDEIRA: I don't know that it felt so much that way. I think we just - it was something that happened. There's a great pride, more so than anything else. We knew he was our hero. We knew he was our legend and it just took a lot of a humble, peaceful man to lead and to have - at this point in my life, realizing how incredibly much of a hero that he really was.


https://people.com/archive/school-bus-kidnapping-the-memories-never-stop-vol-78-no-13/
	Driver Ed Ray, who died May 17 at age 91, emerged as a hero, rallying the children and directing their escape.

	Medrano

	He was a courageous man. He kept 26 scared children in line and made us feel safe.

	Dailey

	We started stacking mattresses. Older kids started digging.

	Medrano

	We were as afraid to get out as to stay in; were they out there? After all of us were out, we started walking. [Finally] a man drove up and said, “Oh my God. You’re those kids.”


https://www.cnn.com/2015/11/19/us/rewind-chowchilla-school-bus-kidnapping/index.html
	Rebecca Reynolds

	God is good all the time love you Ed Ray

	Edward you will be forever my hero

	Love, Angie Robison

	Victims of the school bus kidnapping signed the bus after driver Edward Ray's death in 2012. Ray was hailed as a hero for helping the 26 children escape. 



From accounts, seems clear escape was team effort--kids cheered up Ray, and he, Marshall and Gonzoles worked together to help the rest of the kids out of the buried trailer.

Press gave all the credit to Ray, Mike Marshall and his parents gave all the credit to Marshall, and the press encouraged the fight.

Then Larry park published his book, first in July 2011 then a revised edition in 2016

book goes way over the top in writing Ray out of escape, basically says he didn't want to escape

contradicts other accounts, guessing what happened is Ray was worried kidnappers would be up there


then Park book has a lot of other anomalies:


https://read.amazon.com/?asin=B01LOPTFFU
	...The man holding the bag seemed to have a grin on his face as I took another step down the ladder, as if he were very pleased with himself for what he was doing. The woman just stood there with her hand resting on the arm of the man holding the bag. I wondered if she had children, and if she had put them in a hole too.

	...If this were a joke in any way, this is where they would tell me. Looking at each of them one more time, the images of masked, distorted, evil faces standing there above me were being burned into my brain. Never have I forgotten how those ghouls looked in that instant.

	...Standing on the ladder staring at the men, I waited for them to start laughing and say this was all a joke. Then I felt Ed Ray take hold of my foot and give a little tug.

	...Ed Ray kept his hands on the calves of my legs. With each step I took down the ladder, his steady hands were my guide. ...Ed Ray picked me off the ladder. He set me down, turned me to face, him, and gave he a long look up and down. "Are you okay?" he asked me quietly.

	...None of us said anything because we didn't want the kidnappers to get mad and hurt us as they were continually threatening to do. I could hear the kidnappers talking above us. They were talking so low the words sounded garbled, as if they were speaking a language only they understood. *Didn't demons have their own language?*

	...Ed Ray stood at the base of the ladder waiting and picked her off just as he had done me. As each child was retreived from the aldder, he would give them a gentle push toward the rest of us. I felt *so* very guilty as I watched her climbing into the hole; guilty because I should have done something to save her from this. She came to stand beside me. *She was there, and it was totally my fault! How could I have been such a chicken? How could I let here be trapped like this? Why didn't I run when I had the chance!?*

	"They took my purse," she told me softly. "Mom and Dad are going to be mad." That was my fault too.

	...The kidnappers pulled up the ladder and covered the hole. We were in the darkness again.

	"Hey!" Ed Ray called up. "This isn't all the kids! Were's the rest of the chidlren? What have you done to them?"

	The kidnappers yelled at him to shut up. They said something about the kids being there when they got there.

	...It only took moments for him to get to us. I felt his hand brush my shoulder as he reached out trying to touch each child in the dark. What thoughts had to be going through his mind? He had been driving us back and forth to school all summer. He had laughed with us often, admonished us when necessary, and cared for each of us individually. He knew each of our names, not as a bus route chart, but as individuals. He knew me even when he passed me on the sidewalk. He knew all of us that way.

	Now some of us were missing and he had no idea where they were. Was he saying each name to himself and remembering a smiling face? As he touched each of us who were there with him, was he counting the heads of those who weren't? I feared for those who were missing. Why weren't they there with us? I could feel Ed Ray's presence towing over our group as we stood there in the darkness, and I felt better for his nearness.

	Once he got to us, we crowded around him, hugging him and just trying to touch him simply for the contact. 

	...The cover was taken off the hole once again casting a dim circle of light onto the dirt covered floor. ...as each one stepped off the ladder he would give them a long look. I think he needed to reassure himself that each was whole and unharmed.

	...Then some of us heard the sound of wires snapping. Ping . . . ping. With each ping, the roof of our tomb came down a little more.

	...We children just kept screaming and begging for them to stop.

	Ping, ping, ping. The wires seemed to be singing our death song, a song of hopelessness and doom, and as the roof started falling, we all fell to the floor covering our heads with our arms. The roof was coming down, and we were going to die.

	...Ed Ray didn't have any answers to give, so he again gathered children around him and held us all in a huge hug.

	...I would like to believe what the kidnappers said later about them not leaving us to die, but I don't see how they were going to let us out from Canada where one of them was caught and another of them reportedly tried to go.

	Over the hole on top of the ground they put a piece of plywood and covered that with about eight inches of dirt and then brush, though we didn't know it at the time. Had someone walked right over the top of us, they would never have known it. We were gone. No one would ever see or hear from us again. We had been wiped off the face of the earth the way you grind a spider into the ground. We no longer existed for all intents and purposes.

	...It wasn't long before the smell in the tomb was matching that of being in the back of the van. All of us had to use our makeshift facilities and, one at a time, the curtain was raised to allow each of us in turn to do our business.

	...Ed Ray announced that he was going to be turning out the flashlight to save the batteries while we rested. Some of the children started sobbing again, and there were weak cires of "I want my Momma," and "I just wanna go home." Ed Ray kept going from bed to bed patting the children and speaking to us quietly as he soothed us each in turn.

	...I just wanted Mom and Dad. I just wanted to go home. *What did I do that was so wrong? Why were they punishing me? Did Mom and Dad say this was okay? I wanted my mom. I just wanted my mom!*

	...Not long after Mom and Dad arrived in town, Chowchilla lost electricity. The atmosphere in the house at Aunt Betty's tinged with chill as a feeling of evil seemed to shadow the house for a moment. Many of my aunts and uncles started praying for the Holy Spirit to come and reside with them through the storm.

	"The Devil's in this town tonight," my Aunt Katheryn said. "Satan's here, and God doesn't like it one bit."

	...The whispered singing didn't last long after that; we were still trying to be quiet in case the kidnappers got mad. You might imagine that singing "This Little Light of Mine" is slightly difficult in the pitch darkness of Hell. After a while, I could hear Ed Ray somewhere in the darkness. It sounded like he was crying or something and moaning that we were going to die. Andrea says she also remembers this very clearly.

	It seemed like an eternity that we sat there in the darkness wondering what was going to happen to us, wondering if the monsters would come back to let us out. Then Mike Marshal decided that, if he did have to die, he wasn't going to die without a fight. Enough is enough and he had apparently had just that.

	...Mom just knew we were out there somewhere. She knew we hadn't been taken off the earth, so we *must* be somewhere close by.

	...Mom tried to think about the whole thing analytically. *If they couldn't be hidden without a trace, then waht could've happened? They didn'tt ake the bus, so that means the kids must've been put into something else.

	...But what if they hadn't used a van? What if they'd used something else? What else could they have used to hide twenty-seven people? A semi-truk and trialer? No way. They could never have pulled a semi into and then out of the slough, and they didn't walkt those kids anywhere without leaving some kind of trakcs. How did they do this?* It was impossible to even contemplate. *What if it wasn't a human crime? What if it* was *space people like the authorities jokingly said?

	She tried to imagine Andrea and me flying in outer space with little green men. *Would they take them to far away stars? Would they show them all the different planets? Or would they use them for food? Would they feed them to their young? And how* absolutely ridiculous *was this line of thinking? There* were *no flying saucers, no little green men. There was no one in space wanting to eat her little girl and boy. Thoughts along those lines were absolutely idiotic, and a waste of time. My time's better spent trying to figure out how* men *had done this.


many passages in the book are puzzling

guess the guy has a lot of angst against his parents and Ed Ray

some parts contradict testimony of others, like one of perps being a woman, perps talking to them beyond asking for names

his attacks on Ed Ray and religiosity of Chowchilla residents mirror some of the propaganda in press--where did he get these ideas?

overall effect is to confuse reconstruction of what happened. seems to be motivated by animosity

seems like book didn't get favorable attention in press:

https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2011/07/14/chowchilla-kidnapping-victim-writes-book-2/
	Chowchilla kidnapping victim writes book

	...They escaped their would-be tomb by digging themselves out.

	Park was 6. Although he was not physically hurt, he said it left him with a lifetime of mental problems — from not being able to hold a job, to anger issues with his parents, to violent, gory zombie nightmares.

	“At 41 years, old I still sleep with a night light,” said Park, a Mariposa resident who briefly lived in Concord after the incident.

	Diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia, he recently released a book he wrote to help with his healing: “The Chowchilla Kidnapping: Why Me?” — available electronically for $7.99 at www.smashwords.com/books/view/72803.

	Park said the book was for himself, but also to help others open up about trauma they might be holding inside.

	...Park said it was the second to last day of summer school, and they were returning from a trip to the town pool when men with guns, and stockings over their faces, stopped the bus. His sister, then 8, was also on the trip. Some thought it was a joke, but it wasn’t.

	“It was just dark and scary and I just wanted my mom,” Park said.

	On his second night home, he developed a voice in his head he named Mister. Making matters worse, he said the theory at the time was that the children would get over it easily. Instead, he said he grew to hate his parents and the rest of the world, thinking he had been abandoned and no one cared.

	His family moved to Concord, in an attempt to leave the memories behind. They moved to Mariposa when he was 10. At 12, at Mister’s urging, Park said he killed a chicken. It was the first of many animal killings, which he blamed on dogs. He said it gave him a sense of power.

	Park said his mother was afraid of his behavior and he was sent to foster care. There, he acted out, and at 17 was sent to the California Youth Authority, where he spent three years. Park said adult life has not been easy. His jobs have included being the manager of an apartment complex and at a handyman service, but he has not been able to hold them long, usually leaving when he gets upset. 

	...Park, who attends a nondenominational church that also focuses on sobriety, said he is too close to the case to decide if the perpetrators should be released from prison.

	At parole hearings he has attended, he said it is always mentioned that no one was harmed by the crime, which he doesn’t think is taking responsibility.

	However, he does pray for the kidnappers. On the 35th anniversary of the kidnapping, he plans to be with church leaders and ot sense of power.her close associates.

	“God bless them, because I can’t,” he said.


