	Bates said his investigators found two sets of tracks superimposed on the bus tracks, suggesting that an abduction "would have to be planned, it seems to me." The tracks showed that "somebody left the area after the bus was parked."



July 16 UPI:

https://www.newspapers.com/image/2387706/?terms=Chowchilla
	At the scene investigators found swimming suits and towels in the abandoned bus. Dust patterns on the bus seats led authorities to believe the vehicle was empty at the time it was abandoned.

	...Tracks from perhaps two vehicles besides the bus were found at the scene, but a heavy rain during the night hampered investigation. Authorities said the area often is used by hunters, which might explain the tire tracks.



July 16 AP:


https://www.newspapers.com/image/315175/?terms=Cowchilla
	FBI Director ... Kelly said he has ordered Assistant FBI Director Robert E. Gebhardt of the Los Angeles FBI office to "immediately proceed to Chowchilla (Calif.) to take personal charge of the investigation."


July 16 UPI:


https://www.newspapers.com/image/2387706
	The FBI sent six agents to the scene from its Sacramento office, but Paul C. Young, special agent in charge, said there was no legal basis to declare the disappearance a kidnaping and that the agents were only offering assistance and were not officially assigned to the case.



UPI article tends to throw reader off what turned out to be facts of the case

bit that "tracks ... besides the bus were found at the scene" has to be a lie--in AP article said tracks were found on top of bus tracks, not beside them, and Bates walked through logic of how this means two vehicles left scene after bus left there. Given this, whole UPI article strange.




