https://www.newspapers.com/image/15448155/?terms=Chowchilla
	17 Jul 1976

	CHOWCHILLA, Calif. (UPI) -- "Mr. Ray, he's the best," chanted a group of children when asked who their favorite bus driver was.

	Frank Ray Jr., 55, is also a real homespun hero today after digging himself and 26 children from a cavern prison near Livermore, Calif.

	The folks in his farming community of Chowchilla were certain all along that Ray was never involced in the bizzare abduction of a busload of Dairyland School children.

	"He's too reliable and well loved," said a mother awaiting her daughter before the Friday night's rescue. "If anything, he's out there fighting for those kids."

	The mother was right.

	Ray, his bright blue eyes flashing, said he did most of the digging that freed the children and himself from a cavern at the bottom of a rock quarry where they had been left 16 hours earlier by gunmen.

	...John Brown, an agriculture teacher at Chowchilla High School, had two children aboard the bus, Jeff, 10, and Jennifer, 9. "They'd go anywhere with that bus driver," he said. "He took a lot of their parents to school."

	..."There ain't a kid that dislikes him," added Marion. "He's wonderful with kids."




https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1977/11/03/chowchilla-kidnap-victims-tell-trial-of-fears-in-cave/9534e80b-31a0-4b65-8800-2764292ed353/?utm_term=.3485579d1640
	Jennifer Brown, a Chowchila kidnapping victim who said she is nine and amended it moments later to 10, testified yesterday about the lack of air in the cave in which she and 25 other children and their bus driver were once entombed.

	Sitting in a chair too large, with her feet dangling six inches from the floor, she said the air "started to disappear. It started to get hard to breathe."

	She was asked how she knew the air was disappearing, "Because Irene Carrejo (a 13-year-old kidnapping victim) told me it was."


